## FAQs

**What is an active gaming experience?**
Active gaming is entertainment that requires physical movement as a core part of the game — free-roaming VR arenas, laser mazes, obstacle-style challenge rooms, lit floor grid competitions. Unlike traditional gaming, your whole body is involved, not just your hands.

**Why is active gaming trending in 2026?**
People want social, physical, and memorable experiences over passive entertainment. Active gaming is also highly shareable on social media, scales well for groups of all sizes, and offers a strong contrast to the screen-heavy nature of everyday life.

**Is active gaming suitable for all ages?**
Most venues offer formats across a range of ages. Free-roaming VR and laser mazes typically suit ages 8 and up. Claw machines and casual arcade formats work well for younger kids. Some venues, like Infusion XR Arcade, offer room-scale VR specifically designed for children under 8.

**Do I need to book an active gaming venue in advance?**
Many venues accept walk-ins, which is a big part of the appeal for spontaneous visits. Infusion Play at 546 Yates St welcomes walk-ins and also offers online booking at infusion-play.com for groups who prefer to plan ahead.

**What's the difference between free-roaming VR and regular VR?**
Regular VR is typically room-scale or stationary — you stand or sit in a small space. Free-roaming VR gives you a large physical arena to actually walk and run through, with the virtual environment matching your real movement. Titles like After the Fall and Arizona Sunshine use this format for multiplayer group play.

**Can active gaming venues handle large corporate groups?**
Absolutely. Venues with multiple experience formats, large group capacity, and on-site food and beverages are built for corporate events. Competitive formats across VR, laser maze, and challenge rooms give teams shared goals and natural moments of collaboration.

**What should I wear to an active gaming venue?**
Comfortable clothes and closed-toe shoes. You'll be running, dodging, and moving through physical challenge rooms, so anything you'd wear to a casual workout works perfectly. Leave the dress shoes at home.

